Bury, Lancashire, England","England":"England"},"nl":{"1240–after 1280":"1240–na 1280","1240–1280":"1240–1280","1245–Female":"1245–Overleden","1260–1315":"1260–1315","1274–1300":"1274–1300","1220–1281":"1220–1281","1221–Female":"1221–Overleden","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","after 1280":"na 1280","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","Bury, Lancashire, England":"Bury, Lancashire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1240–after 1280":"1240–after 1280","1240–1280":"1240–1280","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","1260–1315":"1260–1315","1274–1300":"1274–1300","1220–1281":"1220–1281","1221–Female":"1221–Deceased","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","after 1280":"after 1280","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","Bury, Lancashire, England":"Bury, Lancashire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Bury in Lancashire (now part of Greater Manchester), or from some other similarly named place. The placename comes from the dative case, <i>byrig</i>, of Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’.","Walloon and French: habitational name from any of several places so named, in Wallonia (Belgium) and Oise (France). The placename is from <i>Buriacum</i>, the name of a Gallo-Roman estate, composed of the personal name <i>Burius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","South German: variant of   Buri  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Buri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Markus, Kurt.","Swiss German and South German: from an Alemannic pet form of the personal name <i>Burkhard</i> (see   Burkhart  ).","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Buro  ."]},{"name":"Burgh","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Adam de Bury II was born in 1240, in Bury, Lancashire, England, his father, Adam de Bury II, was 21 and his mother, Anabel, was 19. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Baroness Charlotte Talbot. He died after 1280, in his hometown."},"et":{"1240–after 1280":"1240–pärast 1280","1240–1280":"1240–1280","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1260–1315":"1260–1315","1274–1300":"1274–1300","1220–1281":"1220–1281","1221–Female":"1221–Surnud","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","after 1280":"pärast 1280","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","Bury, Lancashire, England":"Bury, Lancashire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1240–after 1280":"1240–1280 jälkeen","1240–1280":"1240–1280","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1260–1315":"1260–1315","1274–1300":"1274–1300","1220–1281":"1220–1281","1221–Female":"1221–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","after 1280":"1280 jälkeen","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1221":"1221","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","Bury, Lancashire, England":"Bury, Lancashire, England","England":"Eng